<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="588" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,1252]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,440,464,487]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">Description. Female.</emphasis>
Body length 
<quantity box="[604,738,464,487]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="1.35" valueMax="1.4" valueMin="1.3">1.3–1.4 mm</quantity>
(n= 
<number box="[792,820,464,487]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="10.0">10</number>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[844,905,464,487]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">Head</emphasis>
. Frons dark, one pair of supra–antennal setae proclinate, positioned in same horizontal line as first two setae, with 
<number box="[915,928,498,521]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="2.0">2</number>
– 
<number box="[942,981,498,521]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4</number>
– 
<number box="[995,1008,498,521]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="4.0">4</number>
setae, also presence of micro setae on frons. Antenna flattened, flagellomere 
<number box="[574,587,533,556]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="1.0">1</number>
conical with arista (
<figureCitation box="[815,880,533,556]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 7" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1953,1975]" captionTargetBox="[162,1429,464,1908]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,455,1929]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 7. Pseudacteon pesqueroi new spec.. 1. Head with emphasis on antennae and forehead. 2. Wing. 3. Oviscape dorsal view (dashed long—stylet, dashed short—oviduct). 4. Palpus. 5. Tergite VI. 6. Sternite VI. 7. Oviscape side view (DP – dorsal plate, VP—ventral plate, O—oviduct, S—stylet). Scale bars equivalent to 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/243523/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">
Fig. 
<number box="[867,880,533,556]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). Palpus yellow with distinct apical setae and 
<number box="[1395,1435,533,556]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4</number>
shorter setae (
<figureCitation box="[301,367,568,591]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 7" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1953,1975]" captionTargetBox="[162,1429,464,1908]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,455,1929]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 7. Pseudacteon pesqueroi new spec.. 1. Head with emphasis on antennae and forehead. 2. Wing. 3. Oviscape dorsal view (dashed long—stylet, dashed short—oviduct). 4. Palpus. 5. Tergite VI. 6. Sternite VI. 7. Oviscape side view (DP – dorsal plate, VP—ventral plate, O—oviduct, S—stylet). Scale bars equivalent to 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/243523/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">
Fig. 
<number box="[351,367,568,591]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[388,479,568,591]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">Thorax.</emphasis>
Scutellum with four setae, posterior twice length of anterior. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1142,1211,568,591]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">Wing.</emphasis>
Length 
<quantity box="[1300,1432,568,591]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="1.0" valueMax="1.2" valueMin="0.8">0.8–1.2 mm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity box="[221,381,602,625]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.85" metricValueMax="5.8" metricValueMin="3.9" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="0.485" valueMax="0.58" valueMin="0.39">0.39–0.58 mm</quantity>
, costal vein 
<quantity box="[521,666,602,625]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.9" metricValueMax="4.8" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="0.39" valueMax="0.48" valueMin="0.3">0.3–0.48 mm</quantity>
with presence 
<number box="[834,900,602,625]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="12.5" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="11.0">11–14</number>
short setae of 
<quantity box="[1066,1164,602,625]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="0.02">0.02 mm</quantity>
(n= 
<number box="[1212,1240,602,625]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="10.0">10</number>
), vein A 
<number box="[1337,1344,618,630]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="1.0">1</number>
+ CuA 
<number box="[1428,1435,618,630]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="2.0">2</number>
present, but in some 
<typeStatus box="[386,488,640,663]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">paratypes</typeStatus>
it is hyaline. Anterior basal region of wing with 
<number box="[1044,1085,640,663]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4</number>
setae (
<figureCitation box="[1166,1235,640,663]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 7" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1953,1975]" captionTargetBox="[162,1429,464,1908]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,455,1929]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 7. Pseudacteon pesqueroi new spec.. 1. Head with emphasis on antennae and forehead. 2. Wing. 3. Oviscape dorsal view (dashed long—stylet, dashed short—oviduct). 4. Palpus. 5. Tergite VI. 6. Sternite VI. 7. Oviscape side view (DP – dorsal plate, VP—ventral plate, O—oviduct, S—stylet). Scale bars equivalent to 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/243523/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">
Fig. 
<number box="[1219,1235,640,663]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1259,1370,640,663]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">Abdomen</emphasis>
. First abdominal segment shorter than the others, tergite VI triangular (
<figureCitation box="[849,913,674,697]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 7" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1953,1975]" captionTargetBox="[162,1429,464,1908]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,455,1929]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 7. Pseudacteon pesqueroi new spec.. 1. Head with emphasis on antennae and forehead. 2. Wing. 3. Oviscape dorsal view (dashed long—stylet, dashed short—oviduct). 4. Palpus. 5. Tergite VI. 6. Sternite VI. 7. Oviscape side view (DP – dorsal plate, VP—ventral plate, O—oviduct, S—stylet). Scale bars equivalent to 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/243523/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">
Fig. 
<number box="[899,913,674,697]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
) with 
<number box="[983,1050,674,697]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="11.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="10.0">10–12</number>
bristles in posterior region. Sternite VI sclerotized (
<figureCitation box="[316,380,709,732]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 7" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1953,1975]" captionTargetBox="[162,1429,464,1908]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,455,1929]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 7. Pseudacteon pesqueroi new spec.. 1. Head with emphasis on antennae and forehead. 2. Wing. 3. Oviscape dorsal view (dashed long—stylet, dashed short—oviduct). 4. Palpus. 5. Tergite VI. 6. Sternite VI. 7. Oviscape side view (DP – dorsal plate, VP—ventral plate, O—oviduct, S—stylet). Scale bars equivalent to 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/243523/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">
Fig. 
<number box="[365,380,709,732]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
), convex, with 
<number box="[545,612,709,732]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="15.0" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="14.0">14–16</number>
bristles, pleural VI with taint. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[939,1043,709,732]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">Oviscape</emphasis>
. Dark brown, ranging from 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.25" metricValueMax="4.8" metricValueMin="3.7" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="0.425" valueMax="0.48" valueMin="0.37">0.37– 0.48 mm</quantity>
long, lobe length outer margin 0,1–0,17 mm and opening between lobes, ranging from 
<quantity box="[1193,1348,744,767]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="0.05" valueMax="0.06" valueMin="0.04">0.04–0.06 mm</quantity>
(n= 
<number box="[1396,1424,744,767]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="10.0">10</number>
). Short and bifurcated, with two plates, dorsal and ventral, articulated anteriorly, center of dorsal plate has a depression with four pairs of setae. (
<figureCitation box="[424,490,813,836]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 7" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1953,1975]" captionTargetBox="[162,1429,464,1908]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,455,1929]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 7. Pseudacteon pesqueroi new spec.. 1. Head with emphasis on antennae and forehead. 2. Wing. 3. Oviscape dorsal view (dashed long—stylet, dashed short—oviduct). 4. Palpus. 5. Tergite VI. 6. Sternite VI. 7. Oviscape side view (DP – dorsal plate, VP—ventral plate, O—oviduct, S—stylet). Scale bars equivalent to 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/243523/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">
Fig. 
<number box="[475,490,813,836]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). In ventral plate is inserted the centerpiece (sternite VIII) lanceolate with four pairs of setae, at base of this piece there is an opening which passes the stylet (Fig. 3,7). Depression on dorsal plate is somewhat sclerotized and rounded in lateral lobes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,1252]" box="[199,383,917,940]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,263,917,940]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">Male.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,974,952,975]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,1252]" box="[199,974,952,975]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,952,975]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">Distribution</emphasis>
. 
<collectingCountry box="[351,465,952,975]" name="Bolivia" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">BOLIVIA</collectingCountry>
: Beni; 
<collectingCountry box="[539,639,952,975]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">BRAZIL</collectingCountry>
: Bahia; 
<collectingCountry box="[726,798,952,975]" name="Peru" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">PERU</collectingCountry>
: Madre de Dios.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="588" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,1252]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,327,986,1009]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named for Dr. Marcos Antônio Pesquero, one of the first Brazilian researchers to start studies with ecology and taxonomy of 
<taxonomicName box="[429,565,1021,1044]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Pseudacteon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[429,565,1021,1044]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">Pseudacteon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="588" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,1252]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,309,1056,1079]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is included in the species group proposed by 
<bibRefCitation box="[992,1222,1056,1079]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" refString="Plowes, R. M., Lebrun, E. G., Brown, B. V. &amp; Gilbert, L. E., (2009) A Review of Pseudacteon (Diptera: Phoridae) that parasitize ants of the Solenopsis geminate complex (hymenoptera: Formicidae). Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 102 (no. 6), 937 - 958. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1603 / 008.102.0604" type="journal article">
Plowes 
<emphasis box="[1081,1140,1056,1079]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[1159,1215,1056,1079]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="2009.0">2009</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
with short, forked oviscape. Within the species group the new species resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Borgmeier, 1926" authorityName="Borgmeier" authorityYear="1926" box="[832,1258,1090,1113]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Pseudacteon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nocens">
<emphasis box="[832,1051,1090,1113]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">Pseudacteon nocens</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Borgmeier" box="[1066,1250,1090,1113]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" refString="Borgmeier, T. (1926) Phorideos Myrmecophilos da Argentina (Dipt.). Boletim do Museu Nacional do Rio de Janeiro, 2, 1 - 16." type="journal article" year="1926">
Borgmeier, 
<number box="[1195,1250,1090,1113]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="1926.0">1926</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Plowes et al. 2009" authorityName="Plowes et al." authorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Pseudacteon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palomita">
<emphasis box="[1313,1436,1090,1113]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">P. palomita</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Plowes" box="[158,365,1125,1148]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" refString="Plowes, R. M., Lebrun, E. G., Brown, B. V. &amp; Gilbert, L. E., (2009) A Review of Pseudacteon (Diptera: Phoridae) that parasitize ants of the Solenopsis geminate complex (hymenoptera: Formicidae). Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 102 (no. 6), 937 - 958. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1603 / 008.102.0604" type="journal article" year="2009">
Plowes 
<emphasis box="[245,301,1125,1148]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[308,365,1125,1148]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" value="2009.0">2009</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, but the depression in 
<taxonomicName box="[621,753,1125,1148]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Pseudacteon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pesqueroi">
<emphasis box="[621,753,1125,1148]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">P. pesqueroi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is less sclerotized than in 
<emphasis box="[1043,1152,1125,1148]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">
<taxonomicName box="[1043,1148,1125,1148]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Pseudacteon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nocens">P. nocens</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Different also because, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Pseudacteon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pesqueroi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">P. pesqueroi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has lobes rounded, truncated in 
<taxonomicName box="[601,817,1160,1183]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Pseudacteon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nocens">
<emphasis box="[601,817,1160,1183]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">Pseudacteon nocens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and facing out in 
<taxonomicName box="[1011,1132,1160,1183]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Pseudacteon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palomita">
<emphasis box="[1011,1132,1160,1183]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">P. palomita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,1252]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,418,1194,1217]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">Field observations.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[481,527,1194,1217]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">type</typeStatus>
specimens were collected associated with a colony of 
<taxonomicName box="[1146,1386,1194,1217]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Solenopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saevissima">
<emphasis box="[1146,1386,1194,1217]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">Solenopsis saevissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[151,370,1229,1252]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Solenopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="geminata">
<emphasis box="[151,370,1229,1252]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="588">Solenopsis geminata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
